py-experiments.etl.pkg.dataframe

Module dataframe insulates external dependencies for the DataFrame abstraction.

Other modules consuming a DataFrame don't have to directly import from dask

 2
 3Other modules consuming a DataFrame don't have to
 4directly import from dask
 5"""

4665class DataFrame(_Frame):
4666    """
4667    Parallel Pandas DataFrame
4668
4669    Do not use this class directly.  Instead use functions like
4670    ``dd.read_csv``, ``dd.read_parquet``, or ``dd.from_pandas``.
4671
4672    Parameters
4673    ----------
4674    dsk: dict
4675        The dask graph to compute this DataFrame
4676    name: str
4677        The key prefix that specifies which keys in the dask comprise this
4678        particular DataFrame
4679    meta: pandas.DataFrame
4680        An empty ``pandas.DataFrame`` with names, dtypes, and index matching
4681        the expected output.
4682    divisions: tuple of index values
4683        Values along which we partition our blocks on the index
4684    """

4686    _partition_type = pd.DataFrame

4691    def __init__(self, dsk, name, meta, divisions):
4692        super().__init__(dsk, name, meta, divisions)
4693        if self.dask.layers[name].collection_annotations is None:
4694            self.dask.layers[name].collection_annotations = {
4695                "npartitions": self.npartitions,
4696                "columns": [col for col in self.columns],
4697                "type": typename(type(self)),
4698                "dataframe_type": typename(type(self._meta)),
4699                "series_dtypes": {
4700                    col: self._meta[col].dtype
4701                    if hasattr(self._meta[col], "dtype")
4702                    else None
4703                    for col in self._meta.columns
4704                },
4705            }
4706        else:
4707            self.dask.layers[name].collection_annotations.update(
4708                {
4709                    "npartitions": self.npartitions,
4710                    "columns": [col for col in self.columns],
4711                    "type": typename(type(self)),
4712                    "dataframe_type": typename(type(self._meta)),
4713                    "series_dtypes": {
4714                        col: self._meta[col].dtype
4715                        if hasattr(self._meta[col], "dtype")
4716                        else None
4717                        for col in self._meta.columns
4718                    },
4719                }
4720            )

4722    def __array_wrap__(self, array, context=None):
4723        if isinstance(context, tuple) and len(context) > 0:
4724            if isinstance(context[1][0], np.ndarray) and context[1][0].shape == ():
4725                index = None
4726            else:
4727                index = context[1][0].index
4728        else:
4729            try:
4730                import inspect
4731
4732                method_name = f"`{inspect.stack()[3][3]}`"
4733            except IndexError:
4734                method_name = "This method"
4735
4736            raise NotImplementedError(
4737                f"{method_name} is not implemented for `dask.dataframe.DataFrame`."
4738            )
4739
4740        return meta_frame_constructor(self)(array, index=index, columns=self.columns)

4758    def iloc(self):
4759        """Purely integer-location based indexing for selection by position.
4760
4761        Only indexing the column positions is supported. Trying to select
4762        row positions will raise a ValueError.
4763
4764        See :ref:`dataframe.indexing` for more.
4765
4766        Examples
4767        --------
4768        >>> df.iloc[:, [2, 0, 1]]  # doctest: +SKIP
4769        """
4770        from dask.dataframe.indexing import _iLocIndexer
4771
4772        # For dataframes with unique column names, this will be transformed into a __getitem__ call
4773        return _iLocIndexer(self)

4775    def __len__(self):
4776        try:
4777            s = self.iloc[:, 0]
4778        except IndexError:
4779            return super().__len__()
4780        else:
4781            return len(s)

4786    @property
4787    def empty(self):
4788        # __getattr__ will be called after we raise this, so we'll raise it again from there
4789        raise AttributeNotImplementedError(
4790            "Checking whether a Dask DataFrame has any rows may be expensive. "
4791            "However, checking the number of columns is fast. "
4792            "Depending on which of these results you need, use either "
4793            "`len(df.index) == 0` or `len(df.columns) == 0`"
4794        )

4796    def __getitem__(self, key):
4797        name = "getitem-%s" % tokenize(self, key)
4798        if np.isscalar(key) or isinstance(key, (tuple, str)):
4799            if isinstance(self._meta.index, (pd.DatetimeIndex, pd.PeriodIndex)):
4800                if key not in self._meta.columns:
4801                    warnings.warn(
4802                        "Indexing a DataFrame with a datetimelike index using a single "
4803                        "string to slice the rows, like `frame[string]`, is deprecated "
4804                        "and will be removed in a future version. Use `frame.loc[string]` "
4805                        "instead.",
4806                        FutureWarning,
4807                    )
4808                    return self.loc[key]
4809
4810            # error is raised from pandas
4811            meta = self._meta[_extract_meta(key)]
4812            dsk = partitionwise_graph(operator.getitem, name, self, key)
4813            graph = HighLevelGraph.from_collections(name, dsk, dependencies=[self])
4814            return new_dd_object(graph, name, meta, self.divisions)
4815        elif isinstance(key, slice):
4816            from pandas.api.types import is_float_dtype
4817
4818            is_integer_slice = any(
4819                isinstance(i, Integral) for i in (key.start, key.step, key.stop)
4820            )
4821            # Slicing with integer labels is always iloc based except for a
4822            # float indexer for some reason
4823            if is_integer_slice and not is_float_dtype(self.index.dtype):
4824                # NOTE: this always fails currently, as iloc is mostly
4825                # unsupported, but we call it anyway here for future-proofing
4826                # and error-attribution purposes
4827                return self.iloc[key]
4828            else:
4829                return self.loc[key]
4830
4831        if isinstance(key, (np.ndarray, list)) or (
4832            not is_dask_collection(key) and (is_series_like(key) or is_index_like(key))
4833        ):
4834            # error is raised from pandas
4835            meta = self._meta[_extract_meta(key)]
4836
4837            dsk = partitionwise_graph(operator.getitem, name, self, key)
4838            graph = HighLevelGraph.from_collections(name, dsk, dependencies=[self])
4839            return new_dd_object(graph, name, meta, self.divisions)
4840        if isinstance(key, Series):
4841            # do not perform dummy calculation, as columns will not be changed.
4842            if self.divisions != key.divisions:
4843                from dask.dataframe.multi import _maybe_align_partitions
4844
4845                self, key = _maybe_align_partitions([self, key])
4846            dsk = partitionwise_graph(operator.getitem, name, self, key)
4847            graph = HighLevelGraph.from_collections(name, dsk, dependencies=[self, key])
4848            return new_dd_object(graph, name, self, self.divisions)
4849        if isinstance(key, DataFrame):
4850            return self.where(key, np.nan)
4851
4852        raise NotImplementedError(key)
4853
4854    def __setitem__(self, key, value):
4855        if isinstance(key, (tuple, list)) and isinstance(value, DataFrame):
4856            df = self.assign(**{k: value[c] for k, c in zip(key, value.columns)})
4857
4858        elif isinstance(key, pd.Index) and not isinstance(value, DataFrame):
4859            key = list(key)
4860            df = self.assign(**{k: value for k in key})
4861        elif (
4862            is_dataframe_like(key)
4863            or is_series_like(key)
4864            or isinstance(key, (DataFrame, Series))
4865        ):
4866            df = self.where(~key, value)
4867        elif not isinstance(key, str):
4868            raise NotImplementedError(f"Item assignment with {type(key)} not supported")
4869        else:
4870            df = self.assign(**{key: value})
4871
4872        self.dask = df.dask
4873        self._name = df._name
4874        self._meta = df._meta
4875        self._divisions = df.divisions
4876
4877    def __delitem__(self, key):
4878        result = self.drop([key], axis=1)
4879        self.dask = result.dask
4880        self._name = result._name
4881        self._meta = result._meta
4882
4883    def __setattr__(self, key, value):
4884        try:
4885            columns = object.__getattribute__(self, "_meta").columns
4886        except AttributeError:
4887            columns = ()
4888
4889        # exclude protected attributes from setitem
4890        if key in columns and key not in ["divisions", "dask", "_name", "_meta"]:
4891            self[key] = value
4892        else:
4893            object.__setattr__(self, key, value)
4894
4895    def __getattr__(self, key):
4896        if key in self.columns:
4897            return self[key]
4898        elif key == "empty":
4899            # self.empty raises AttributeNotImplementedError, which includes
4900            # AttributeError, which means we end up here in self.__getattr__,
4901            # because DataFrame.__getattribute__ doesn't think the attribute exists
4902            # and uses __getattr__ as the fallback. So, get `self.empty` more
4903            # forcefully via object.__getattribute__ to raise informative error.
4904            object.__getattribute__(self, key)
4905        else:
4906            raise AttributeError("'DataFrame' object has no attribute %r" % key)
4907
4908    def __dir__(self):
4909        o = set(dir(type(self)))
4910        o.update(self.__dict__)
4911        o.update(c for c in self.columns if (isinstance(c, str) and c.isidentifier()))
4912        return list(o)
4913
4914    def __iter__(self):
4915        return iter(self._meta)

4920    @property

4925    @property
4926    def shape(self):
4927        """
4928        Return a tuple representing the dimensionality of the DataFrame.
4929
4930        The number of rows is a Delayed result. The number of columns
4931        is a concrete integer.
4932
4933        Examples
4934        --------
4935        >>> df.size  # doctest: +SKIP
4936        (Delayed('int-07f06075-5ecc-4d77-817e-63c69a9188a8'), 2)
4937        """
4938        col_size = len(self.columns)
4939        if col_size == 0:
4940            return (self.index.shape[0], 0)
4941        row_size = delayed(int)(self.size / col_size)
4942        return (row_size, col_size)
4943

4959        cs = self._meta.select_dtypes(include=include, exclude=exclude).columns

4962    def sort_values(
4963        self,
4964        by: str | list[str],
4965        npartitions: int | Literal["auto"] | None = None,
4966        ascending: bool = True,
4967        na_position: Literal["first"] | Literal["last"] = "last",
4968        sort_function: Callable[[pd.DataFrame], pd.DataFrame] | None = None,
4969        sort_function_kwargs: Mapping[str, Any] | None = None,
4970        **kwargs,
4971    ) -> DataFrame:
4972        """Sort the dataset by a single column.
4973
4974        Sorting a parallel dataset requires expensive shuffles and is generally
4975        not recommended. See ``set_index`` for implementation details.
4976
4977        Parameters
4978        ----------
4979        by: str or list[str]
4980            Column(s) to sort by.
4981        npartitions: int, None, or 'auto'
4982            The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as
4983            the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use.
4984        ascending: bool, optional
4985            Sort ascending vs. descending.
4986            Defaults to True.
4987        na_position: {'last', 'first'}, optional
4988            Puts NaNs at the beginning if 'first', puts NaN at the end if 'last'.
4989            Defaults to 'last'.
4990        sort_function: function, optional
4991            Sorting function to use when sorting underlying partitions.
4992            If None, defaults to ``M.sort_values`` (the partition library's
4993            implementation of ``sort_values``).
4994        sort_function_kwargs: dict, optional
4995            Additional keyword arguments to pass to the partition sorting function.
4996            By default, ``by``, ``ascending``, and ``na_position`` are provided.
4997
4998        Examples
4999        --------
5000        >>> df2 = df.sort_values('x')  # doctest: +SKIP
5001        """
5002        from dask.dataframe.shuffle import sort_values
5003
5004        return sort_values(
5005            self,
5006            by,
5007            ascending=ascending,
5008            npartitions=npartitions,
5009            na_position=na_position,
5010            sort_function=sort_function,
5011            sort_function_kwargs=sort_function_kwargs,
5012            **kwargs,
5013        )
5014
5015    def set_index(
5016        self,
5017        other: str | Series,
5018        drop: bool = True,
5019        sorted: bool = False,
5020        npartitions: int | Literal["auto"] | None = None,
5021        divisions: Sequence | None = None,
5022        inplace: bool = False,
5023        **kwargs,
5024    ):
5025        """Set the DataFrame index (row labels) using an existing column.
5026
5027        This realigns the dataset to be sorted by a new column. This can have a
5028        significant impact on performance, because joins, groupbys, lookups, etc.
5029        are all much faster on that column. However, this performance increase
5030        comes with a cost, sorting a parallel dataset requires expensive shuffles.
5031        Often we ``set_index`` once directly after data ingest and filtering and
5032        then perform many cheap computations off of the sorted dataset.
5033
5034        This function operates exactly like ``pandas.set_index`` except with
5035        different performance costs (dask dataframe ``set_index`` is much more expensive).
5036        Under normal operation this function does an initial pass over the index column
5037        to compute approximate quantiles to serve as future divisions. It then passes
5038        over the data a second time, splitting up each input partition into several
5039        pieces and sharing those pieces to all of the output partitions now in
5040        sorted order.
5041
5042        In some cases we can alleviate those costs, for example if your dataset is
5043        sorted already then we can avoid making many small pieces or if you know
5044        good values to split the new index column then we can avoid the initial
5045        pass over the data. For example if your new index is a datetime index and
5046        your data is already sorted by day then this entire operation can be done
5047        for free. You can control these options with the following parameters.
5048
5049        Parameters
5050        ----------
5051        other: string or Dask Series
5052            Column to use as index.
5053        drop: boolean, default True
5054            Delete column to be used as the new index.
5055        sorted: bool, optional
5056            If the index column is already sorted in increasing order.
5057            Defaults to False
5058        npartitions: int, None, or 'auto'
5059            The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as
5060            the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use.
5061            Only used when ``divisions`` is not given. If ``divisions`` is given,
5062            the number of output partitions will be ``len(divisions) - 1``.
5063        divisions: list, optional
5064            The "dividing lines" used to split the new index into partitions.
5065            For ``divisions=[0, 10, 50, 100]``, there would be three output partitions,
5066            where the new index contained [0, 10), [10, 50), and [50, 100), respectively.
5067            See https://docs.dask.org/en/latest/dataframe-design.html#partitions.
5068            If not given (default), good divisions are calculated by immediately computing
5069            the data and looking at the distribution of its values. For large datasets,
5070            this can be expensive.
5071            Note that if ``sorted=True``, specified divisions are assumed to match
5072            the existing partitions in the data; if this is untrue you should
5073            leave divisions empty and call ``repartition`` after ``set_index``.
5074        inplace: bool, optional
5075            Modifying the DataFrame in place is not supported by Dask.
5076            Defaults to False.
5077        shuffle: string, 'disk' or 'tasks', optional
5078            Either ``'disk'`` for single-node operation or ``'tasks'`` for
5079            distributed operation.  Will be inferred by your current scheduler.
5080        compute: bool, default False
5081            Whether or not to trigger an immediate computation. Defaults to False.
5082            Note, that even if you set ``compute=False``, an immediate computation
5083            will still be triggered if ``divisions`` is ``None``.
5084        partition_size: int, optional
5085            Desired size of each partitions in bytes.
5086            Only used when ``npartitions='auto'``
5087
5088        Examples
5089        --------
5090        >>> import dask
5091        >>> ddf = dask.datasets.timeseries(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq="1H").reset_index()
5092        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("x")
5093        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.x)
5094        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.timestamp, sorted=True)
5095
5096        A common case is when we have a datetime column that we know to be
5097        sorted and is cleanly divided by day.  We can set this index for free
5098        by specifying both that the column is pre-sorted and the particular
5099        divisions along which is is separated
5100
5101        >>> import pandas as pd
5102        >>> divisions = pd.date_range(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq='1D')
5103        >>> divisions
5104        DatetimeIndex(['2021-01-01', '2021-01-02', '2021-01-03', '2021-01-04',
5105                       '2021-01-05', '2021-01-06', '2021-01-07'],
5106                      dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='D')
5107
5108        Note that ``len(divisons)`` is equal to ``npartitions + 1``. This is because ``divisions``
5109        represents the upper and lower bounds of each partition. The first item is the
5110        lower bound of the first partition, the second item is the lower bound of the
5111        second partition and the upper bound of the first partition, and so on.
5112        The second-to-last item is the lower bound of the last partition, and the last
5113        (extra) item is the upper bound of the last partition.
5114
5115        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("timestamp", sorted=True, divisions=divisions.tolist())
5116
5117        If you'll be running `set_index` on the same (or similar) datasets repeatedly,
5118        you could save time by letting Dask calculate good divisions once, then copy-pasting
5119        them to reuse. This is especially helpful running in a Jupyter notebook:
5120
5121        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name")  # slow, calculates data distribution
5122        >>> ddf2.divisions  # doctest: +SKIP
5123        ["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"]
5124        >>> # ^ Now copy-paste this and edit the line above to:
5125        >>> # ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name", divisions=["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"])
5126        """
5127
5128        if inplace:
5129            raise NotImplementedError("The inplace= keyword is not supported")
5130        pre_sorted = sorted
5131        del sorted
5132
5133        # Check other can be translated to column name or column object, possibly flattening it
5134        if not isinstance(other, str):
5135            # It may refer to several columns
5136            if isinstance(other, Sequence):  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5137                # Accept ["a"], but not [["a"]]
5138                if len(other) == 1 and (  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5139                    isinstance(other[0], str) or not isinstance(other[0], Sequence)
5140                ):
5141                    other = other[0]
5142                else:
5143                    raise NotImplementedError(
5144                        "Dask dataframe does not yet support multi-indexes.\n"
5145                        f"You tried to index with this index: {other}\n"
5146                        "Indexes must be single columns only."
5147                    )
5148
5149            # Or be a frame directly
5150            elif isinstance(other, DataFrame):  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5151                raise NotImplementedError(
5152                    "Dask dataframe does not yet support multi-indexes.\n"
5153                    f"You tried to index with a frame with these columns: {list(other.columns)}\n"
5154                    "Indexes must be single columns only."
5155                )
5156
5157        # If already a series
5158        if isinstance(other, Series):
5159            # If it's already the index, there's nothing to do
5160            if other._name == self.index._name:
5161                warnings.warn(
5162                    "New index has same name as existing, this is a no-op.", UserWarning
5163                )
5164                return self
5165
5166        # If the name of a column/index
5167        else:
5168            # With the same name as the index, there's nothing to do either
5169            if other == self.index.name:
5170                warnings.warn(
5171                    "New index has same name as existing, this is a no-op.", UserWarning
5172                )
5173                return self
5174
5175            # If a missing column, KeyError
5176            if other not in self.columns:
5177                raise KeyError(
5178                    f"Data has no column '{other}': use any column of {list(self.columns)}"
5179                )
5180
5181        # Check divisions
5182        if divisions is not None:
5183            check_divisions(divisions)
5184        elif (
5185            isinstance(other, Index)
5186            and other.known_divisions
5187            and other.npartitions == self.npartitions
5188        ):
5189            # If the index has the same number of partitions and known
5190            # divisions, then we can treat it as pre-sorted with known
5191            # divisions
5192            pre_sorted = True
5193            divisions = other.divisions
5194
5195        # If index is already sorted, take advantage of that with set_sorted_index
5196        if pre_sorted:
5197            from dask.dataframe.shuffle import set_sorted_index
5198
5199            return set_sorted_index(
5200                self, other, drop=drop, divisions=divisions, **kwargs
5201            )
5202        else:
5203            from dask.dataframe.shuffle import set_index
5204
5205            return set_index(
5206                self,
5207                other,
5208                drop=drop,
5209                npartitions=npartitions,
5210                divisions=divisions,
5211                **kwargs,
5212            )
5213

5216        out = self[item]
5217        del self[item]
5218        return out

5276    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5277    def assign(self, **kwargs):
5278        data = self.copy()
5279        for k, v in kwargs.items():
5280            if not (
5281                isinstance(v, Scalar)
5282                or is_series_like(v)
5283                or callable(v)
5284                or pd.api.types.is_scalar(v)
5285                or is_index_like(v)
5286                or isinstance(v, Array)
5287            ):
5288                raise TypeError(
5289                    f"Column assignment doesn't support type {typename(type(v))}"
5290                )
5291            if callable(v):
5292                kwargs[k] = v(data)
5293            if isinstance(v, Array):
5294                from dask.dataframe.io import from_dask_array
5295
5296                if len(v.shape) > 1:
5297                    raise ValueError("Array assignment only supports 1-D arrays")
5298                if v.npartitions != data.npartitions:
5299                    raise ValueError(
5300                        "Number of partitions do not match "
5301                        f"({v.npartitions} != {data.npartitions})"
5302                    )
5303                kwargs[k] = from_dask_array(v, index=data.index, meta=data._meta)
5304
5305            pairs = [k, kwargs[k]]
5306
5307            # Figure out columns of the output
5308            df2 = data._meta_nonempty.assign(
5309                **_extract_meta({k: kwargs[k]}, nonempty=True)
5310            )
5311            data = elemwise(methods.assign, data, *pairs, meta=df2)
5312
5313        return data

5318            raise ValueError("Cannot rename index.")
5319
5320        # *args here is index, columns but columns arg is already used
5321        return self.map_partitions(M.rename, None, columns=columns)

5323    def query(self, expr, **kwargs):
5324        """Filter dataframe with complex expression
5325
5326        Blocked version of pd.DataFrame.query
5327
5328        Parameters
5329        ----------
5330        expr: str
5331            The query string to evaluate.
5332            You can refer to column names that are not valid Python variable names
5333            by surrounding them in backticks.
5334            Dask does not fully support referring to variables using the '@' character,
5335            use f-strings or the ``local_dict`` keyword argument instead.
5336
5337        Notes
5338        -----
5339        This is like the sequential version except that this will also happen
5340        in many threads.  This may conflict with ``numexpr`` which will use
5341        multiple threads itself.  We recommend that you set ``numexpr`` to use a
5342        single thread:
5343
5344        .. code-block:: python
5345
5346            import numexpr
5347            numexpr.set_num_threads(1)
5348
5349        See also
5350        --------
5351        pandas.DataFrame.query
5352        pandas.eval
5353
5354        Examples
5355        --------
5356        >>> import pandas as pd
5357        >>> import dask.dataframe as dd
5358        >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'x': [1, 2, 1, 2],
5359        ...                    'y': [1, 2, 3, 4],
5360        ...                    'z z': [4, 3, 2, 1]})
5361        >>> ddf = dd.from_pandas(df, npartitions=2)
5362
5363        Refer to column names directly:
5364
5365        >>> ddf.query('y > x').compute()
5366           x  y  z z
5367        2  1  3    2
5368        3  2  4    1
5369
5370        Refer to column name using backticks:
5371
5372        >>> ddf.query('`z z` > x').compute()
5373           x  y  z z
5374        0  1  1    4
5375        1  2  2    3
5376        2  1  3    2
5377
5378        Refer to variable name using f-strings:
5379
5380        >>> value = 1
5381        >>> ddf.query(f'x == {value}').compute()
5382           x  y  z z
5383        0  1  1    4
5384        2  1  3    2
5385
5386        Refer to variable name using ``local_dict``:
5387
5388        >>> ddf.query('x == @value', local_dict={"value": value}).compute()
5389           x  y  z z
5390        0  1  1    4
5391        2  1  3    2
5392        """
5393        return self.map_partitions(M.query, expr, **kwargs)
5394
5395    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5396    def eval(self, expr, inplace=None, **kwargs):
5397        if inplace is None:
5398            inplace = False
5399        if "=" in expr and inplace in (True, None):
5400            raise NotImplementedError(
5401                "Inplace eval not supported. Please use inplace=False"
5402            )
5403        meta = self._meta.eval(expr, inplace=inplace, **kwargs)
5404        return self.map_partitions(M.eval, expr, meta=meta, inplace=inplace, **kwargs)

5406    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5407    def dropna(self, how=no_default, subset=None, thresh=no_default):
5408        # These keywords are incompatible with each other.
5409        # Don't allow them both to be set.
5410        if how is not no_default and thresh is not no_default:
5411            raise TypeError(
5412                "You cannot set both the how and thresh arguments at the same time."
5413            )
5414
5415        # Only specify `how` or `thresh` keyword if specified by the user
5416        # so we utilize other `dropna` keyword defaults appropriately
5417        kwargs = {"subset": subset}
5418        if how is not no_default:
5419            kwargs["how"] = how
5420        elif thresh is not no_default:
5421            kwargs["thresh"] = thresh
5422
5423        return self.map_partitions(M.dropna, **kwargs, enforce_metadata=False)

5445    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5446    def squeeze(self, axis=None):
5447        if axis in [None, 1]:
5448            if len(self.columns) == 1:
5449                return self[self.columns[0]]
5450            else:
5451                return self
5452
5453        elif axis == 0:
5454            raise NotImplementedError(
5455                f"{type(self)} does not support squeeze along axis 0"
5456            )
5457
5458        elif axis not in [0, 1, None]:
5459            raise ValueError(f"No axis {axis} for object type {type(self)}")

5507    def _get_numeric_data(self, how="any", subset=None):
5508        # calculate columns to avoid unnecessary calculation
5509        numerics = self._meta._get_numeric_data()
5510

5518    @classmethod
5519    def _validate_axis(cls, axis=0, none_is_zero: bool = True) -> None | Literal[0, 1]:
5520        if axis not in (0, 1, "index", "columns", None):
5521            raise ValueError(f"No axis named {axis}")
5522        # convert to numeric axis
5523        numeric_axis: dict[str | None, Literal[0, 1]] = {"index": 0, "columns": 1}
5524        if none_is_zero:
5525            numeric_axis[None] = 0
5526
5527        return numeric_axis.get(axis, axis)

5529    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5530    def drop(self, labels=None, axis=0, columns=None, errors="raise"):
5531        axis = self._validate_axis(axis)
5532        if axis == 0 and columns is not None:
5533            # Columns must be specified if axis==0
5534            return self.map_partitions(drop_by_shallow_copy, columns, errors=errors)
5535        elif axis == 1:
5536            return self.map_partitions(drop_by_shallow_copy, labels, errors=errors)
5537        raise NotImplementedError(
5538            "Drop currently only works for axis=1 or when columns is not None"
5539        )

5541    def merge(
5542        self,
5543        right,
5544        how="inner",
5545        on=None,
5546        left_on=None,
5547        right_on=None,
5548        left_index=False,
5549        right_index=False,
5550        suffixes=("_x", "_y"),
5551        indicator=False,
5552        npartitions=None,
5553        shuffle=None,
5554        broadcast=None,
5555    ):
5556        """Merge the DataFrame with another DataFrame
5557
5558        This will merge the two datasets, either on the indices, a certain column
5559        in each dataset or the index in one dataset and the column in another.
5560
5561        Parameters
5562        ----------
5563        right: dask.dataframe.DataFrame
5564        how : {'left', 'right', 'outer', 'inner'}, default: 'inner'
5565            How to handle the operation of the two objects:
5566
5567            - left: use calling frame's index (or column if on is specified)
5568            - right: use other frame's index
5569            - outer: form union of calling frame's index (or column if on is
5570              specified) with other frame's index, and sort it
5571              lexicographically
5572            - inner: form intersection of calling frame's index (or column if
5573              on is specified) with other frame's index, preserving the order
5574              of the calling's one
5575
5576        on : label or list
5577            Column or index level names to join on. These must be found in both
5578            DataFrames. If on is None and not merging on indexes then this
5579            defaults to the intersection of the columns in both DataFrames.
5580        left_on : label or list, or array-like
5581            Column to join on in the left DataFrame. Other than in pandas
5582            arrays and lists are only support if their length is 1.
5583        right_on : label or list, or array-like
5584            Column to join on in the right DataFrame. Other than in pandas
5585            arrays and lists are only support if their length is 1.
5586        left_index : boolean, default False
5587            Use the index from the left DataFrame as the join key.
5588        right_index : boolean, default False
5589            Use the index from the right DataFrame as the join key.
5590        suffixes : 2-length sequence (tuple, list, ...)
5591            Suffix to apply to overlapping column names in the left and
5592            right side, respectively
5593        indicator : boolean or string, default False
5594            If True, adds a column to output DataFrame called "_merge" with
5595            information on the source of each row. If string, column with
5596            information on source of each row will be added to output DataFrame,
5597            and column will be named value of string. Information column is
5598            Categorical-type and takes on a value of "left_only" for observations
5599            whose merge key only appears in `left` DataFrame, "right_only" for
5600            observations whose merge key only appears in `right` DataFrame,
5601            and "both" if the observation’s merge key is found in both.
5602        npartitions: int or None, optional
5603            The ideal number of output partitions. This is only utilised when
5604            performing a hash_join (merging on columns only). If ``None`` then
5605            ``npartitions = max(lhs.npartitions, rhs.npartitions)``.
5606            Default is ``None``.
5607        shuffle: {'disk', 'tasks'}, optional
5608            Either ``'disk'`` for single-node operation or ``'tasks'`` for
5609            distributed operation.  Will be inferred by your current scheduler.
5610        broadcast: boolean or float, optional
5611            Whether to use a broadcast-based join in lieu of a shuffle-based
5612            join for supported cases.  By default, a simple heuristic will be
5613            used to select the underlying algorithm. If a floating-point value
5614            is specified, that number will be used as the ``broadcast_bias``
5615            within the simple heuristic (a large number makes Dask more likely
5616            to choose the ``broacast_join`` code path). See ``broadcast_join``
5617            for more information.
5618
5619        Notes
5620        -----
5621
5622        There are three ways to join dataframes:
5623
5624        1. Joining on indices. In this case the divisions are
5625           aligned using the function ``dask.dataframe.multi.align_partitions``.
5626           Afterwards, each partition is merged with the pandas merge function.
5627
5628        2. Joining one on index and one on column. In this case the divisions of
5629           dataframe merged by index (:math:`d_i`) are used to divide the column
5630           merged dataframe (:math:`d_c`) one using
5631           ``dask.dataframe.multi.rearrange_by_divisions``. In this case the
5632           merged dataframe (:math:`d_m`) has the exact same divisions
5633           as (:math:`d_i`). This can lead to issues if you merge multiple rows from
5634           (:math:`d_c`) to one row in (:math:`d_i`).
5635
5636        3. Joining both on columns. In this case a hash join is performed using
5637           ``dask.dataframe.multi.hash_join``.
5638
5639        In some cases, you may see a ``MemoryError`` if the ``merge`` operation requires
5640        an internal ``shuffle``, because shuffling places all rows that have the same
5641        index in the same partition. To avoid this error, make sure all rows with the
5642        same ``on``-column value can fit on a single partition.
5643        """
5644
5645        if not is_dataframe_like(right):
5646            raise ValueError("right must be DataFrame")
5647
5648        from dask.dataframe.multi import merge
5649
5650        return merge(
5651            self,
5652            right,
5653            how=how,
5654            on=on,
5655            left_on=left_on,
5656            right_on=right_on,
5657            left_index=left_index,
5658            right_index=right_index,
5659            suffixes=suffixes,
5660            npartitions=npartitions,
5661            indicator=indicator,
5662            shuffle=shuffle,
5663            broadcast=broadcast,
5664        )
5665
5666    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5667    def join(
5668        self,
5669        other,
5670        on=None,
5671        how="left",
5672        lsuffix="",
5673        rsuffix="",
5674        npartitions=None,
5675        shuffle=None,
5676    ):
5677        if is_series_like(other) and hasattr(other, "name"):
5678            other = other.to_frame()
5679
5680        if not is_dataframe_like(other):
5681            if not isinstance(other, list) or not all(
5682                [is_dataframe_like(o) for o in other]
5683            ):
5684                raise ValueError("other must be DataFrame or list of DataFrames")
5685            if how not in ["outer", "left"]:
5686                raise ValueError("merge_multi only supports left or outer joins")
5687
5688            from dask.dataframe.multi import _recursive_pairwise_outer_join
5689
5690            # If its an outer join we can use the full recursive pairwise join.
5691            if how == "outer":
5692                full = [self] + other
5693
5694                return _recursive_pairwise_outer_join(
5695                    full,
5696                    on=on,
5697                    lsuffix=lsuffix,
5698                    rsuffix=rsuffix,
5699                    npartitions=npartitions,
5700                    shuffle=shuffle,
5701                )
5702            else:
5703                # Do recursive pairwise join on everything _except_ the last join
5704                # where we need to do a left join.
5705                other = _recursive_pairwise_outer_join(
5706                    other,
5707                    on=on,
5708                    lsuffix=lsuffix,
5709                    rsuffix=rsuffix,
5710                    npartitions=npartitions,
5711                    shuffle=shuffle,
5712                )
5713
5714        from dask.dataframe.multi import merge
5715
5716        return merge(
5717            self,
5718            other,
5719            how=how,
5720            left_index=on is None,
5721            right_index=True,
5722            left_on=on,
5723            suffixes=(lsuffix, rsuffix),
5724            npartitions=npartitions,
5725            shuffle=shuffle,
5726        )
5727
5728    if not PANDAS_GT_200:
5729
5730        @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5731        def append(self, other, interleave_partitions=False):
5732            if isinstance(other, Series):
5733                msg = (
5734                    "Unable to appending dd.Series to dd.DataFrame."
5735                    "Use pd.Series to append as row."
5736                )
5737                raise ValueError(msg)
5738            elif is_series_like(other):
5739                other = other.to_frame().T
5740            return super().append(other, interleave_partitions=interleave_partitions)

5759    @classmethod
5760    def _bind_operator_method(cls, name, op, original=pd.DataFrame):
5761        """bind operator method like DataFrame.add to this class"""
5762
5763        # name must be explicitly passed for div method whose name is truediv
5764
5765        def meth(self, other, axis="columns", level=None, fill_value=None):
5766            if level is not None:
5767                raise NotImplementedError("level must be None")
5768
5769            axis = self._validate_axis(axis)
5770
5771            if axis in (1, "columns"):
5772                # When axis=1 and other is a series, `other` is transposed
5773                # and the operator is applied broadcast across rows. This
5774                # isn't supported with dd.Series.
5775                if isinstance(other, Series):
5776                    msg = f"Unable to {name} dd.Series with axis=1"
5777                    raise ValueError(msg)
5778                elif is_series_like(other):
5779                    # Special case for pd.Series to avoid unwanted partitioning
5780                    # of other. We pass it in as a kwarg to prevent this.
5781                    meta = _emulate(
5782                        op, self, other=other, axis=axis, fill_value=fill_value
5783                    )
5784                    return map_partitions(
5785                        op,
5786                        self,
5787                        other=other,
5788                        meta=meta,
5789                        axis=axis,
5790                        fill_value=fill_value,
5791                        enforce_metadata=False,
5792                    )
5793
5794            meta = _emulate(op, self, other, axis=axis, fill_value=fill_value)
5795            return map_partitions(
5796                op,
5797                self,
5798                other,
5799                meta=meta,
5800                axis=axis,
5801                fill_value=fill_value,
5802                enforce_metadata=False,
5803            )
5804
5805        meth.__name__ = name
5806        setattr(cls, name, derived_from(original)(meth))
5807
5808    @classmethod
5809    def _bind_comparison_method(cls, name, comparison, original=pd.DataFrame):
5810        """bind comparison method like DataFrame.eq to this class"""
5811
5812        def meth(self, other, axis="columns", level=None):
5813            if level is not None:
5814                raise NotImplementedError("level must be None")
5815            axis = self._validate_axis(axis)
5816            return elemwise(comparison, self, other, axis=axis)
5817
5818        meth.__name__ = name
5819        setattr(cls, name, derived_from(original)(meth))
5820
5821    @insert_meta_param_description(pad=12)
5822    def apply(
5823        self,
5824        func,
5825        axis=0,
5826        broadcast=None,
5827        raw=False,
5828        reduce=None,
5829        args=(),
5830        meta=no_default,
5831        result_type=None,
5832        **kwds,
5833    ):
5834        """Parallel version of pandas.DataFrame.apply
5835
5836        This mimics the pandas version except for the following:
5837
5838        1.  Only ``axis=1`` is supported (and must be specified explicitly).
5839        2.  The user should provide output metadata via the `meta` keyword.
5840
5841        Parameters
5842        ----------
5843        func : function
5844            Function to apply to each column/row
5845        axis : {0 or 'index', 1 or 'columns'}, default 0
5846            - 0 or 'index': apply function to each column (NOT SUPPORTED)
5847            - 1 or 'columns': apply function to each row
5848        $META
5849        args : tuple
5850            Positional arguments to pass to function in addition to the array/series
5851
5852        Additional keyword arguments will be passed as keywords to the function
5853
5854        Returns
5855        -------
5856        applied : Series or DataFrame
5857
5858        Examples
5859        --------
5860        >>> import pandas as pd
5861        >>> import dask.dataframe as dd
5862        >>> df = pd.DataFrame({'x': [1, 2, 3, 4, 5],
5863        ...                    'y': [1., 2., 3., 4., 5.]})
5864        >>> ddf = dd.from_pandas(df, npartitions=2)
5865
5866        Apply a function to row-wise passing in extra arguments in ``args`` and
5867        ``kwargs``:
5868
5869        >>> def myadd(row, a, b=1):
5870        ...     return row.sum() + a + b
5871        >>> res = ddf.apply(myadd, axis=1, args=(2,), b=1.5)  # doctest: +SKIP
5872
5873        By default, dask tries to infer the output metadata by running your
5874        provided function on some fake data. This works well in many cases, but
5875        can sometimes be expensive, or even fail. To avoid this, you can
5876        manually specify the output metadata with the ``meta`` keyword. This
5877        can be specified in many forms, for more information see
5878        ``dask.dataframe.utils.make_meta``.
5879
5880        Here we specify the output is a Series with name ``'x'``, and dtype
5881        ``float64``:
5882
5883        >>> res = ddf.apply(myadd, axis=1, args=(2,), b=1.5, meta=('x', 'f8'))
5884
5885        In the case where the metadata doesn't change, you can also pass in
5886        the object itself directly:
5887
5888        >>> res = ddf.apply(lambda row: row + 1, axis=1, meta=ddf)
5889
5890        See Also
5891        --------
5892        dask.DataFrame.map_partitions
5893        """
5894
5895        if broadcast is not None:
5896            warnings.warn(
5897                "The `broadcast` argument is no longer used/supported. "
5898                "It will be dropped in a future release.",
5899                category=FutureWarning,
5900            )
5901
5902        axis = self._validate_axis(axis)
5903        pandas_kwargs = {"axis": axis, "raw": raw, "result_type": result_type}
5904
5905        kwds.update(pandas_kwargs)
5906
5907        if axis == 0:
5908            msg = (
5909                "dd.DataFrame.apply only supports axis=1\n"
5910                "  Try: df.apply(func, axis=1)"
5911            )
5912            raise NotImplementedError(msg)
5913
5914        if meta is no_default:
5915            meta = _emulate(
5916                M.apply, self._meta_nonempty, func, args=args, udf=True, **kwds
5917            )
5918            warnings.warn(meta_warning(meta))
5919        kwds.update({"parent_meta": self._meta})
5920        return map_partitions(M.apply, self, func, args=args, meta=meta, **kwds)
5921
5922    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5923    def applymap(self, func, meta=no_default):
5924        # Let pandas raise deprecation warnings
5925        self._meta.applymap(func)
5926        return elemwise(methods.applymap, self, func, meta=meta)

5931                f"DataFrame.map requires pandas>=2.1.0, but pandas={PANDAS_VERSION} is "
5932                "installed."
5933            )
5934        return elemwise(M.map, self, func, meta=meta)

5940    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5941    def nunique(self, split_every=False, dropna=True, axis=0):
5942        if axis == 1:
5943            # split_every not used for axis=1
5944            meta = self._meta_nonempty.nunique(axis=axis)
5945            return self.map_partitions(
5946                M.nunique,
5947                meta=meta,
5948                token="series-nunique",
5949                axis=axis,
5950                dropna=dropna,
5951                enforce_metadata=False,
5952            )
5953        else:
5954            nunique_list = [
5955                self[col].nunique(split_every=split_every, dropna=dropna)
5956                for col in self.columns
5957            ]
5958            name = "series-" + tokenize(*nunique_list)
5959            dsk = {
5960                (name, 0): (
5961                    apply,
5962                    pd.Series,
5963                    [[(s._name, 0) for s in nunique_list]],
5964                    {"index": self.columns},
5965                )
5966            }
5967            graph = HighLevelGraph.from_collections(
5968                name, dsk, dependencies=nunique_list
5969            )
5970            return Series(graph, name, self._meta.nunique(), (None, None))
5971
5972    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
5973    def mode(self, dropna=True, split_every=False, numeric_only=False):
5974        mode_series_list = []
5975        for col_index in range(len(self.columns)):
5976            col_series = self.iloc[:, col_index]
5977            if numeric_only and not pd.api.types.is_numeric_dtype(col_series.dtype):
5978                continue
5979            mode_series = Series.mode(
5980                col_series, dropna=dropna, split_every=split_every
5981            )
5982            mode_series_list.append(mode_series)
5983
5984        name = "concat-" + tokenize(*mode_series_list)
5985
5986        dsk = {
5987            (name, 0): (
5988                apply,
5989                methods.concat,
5990                [[(df._name, 0) for df in mode_series_list]],
5991                {"axis": 1},
5992            )
5993        }
5994
5995        meta = methods.concat([df._meta for df in mode_series_list], axis=1)
5996        graph = HighLevelGraph.from_collections(
5997            name, dsk, dependencies=mode_series_list
5998        )
5999        ddf = new_dd_object(graph, name, meta, divisions=(None, None))
6000
6001        return ddf

6024    def info(self, buf=None, verbose=False, memory_usage=False):
6025        """
6026        Concise summary of a Dask DataFrame.
6027        """
6028
6029        if buf is None:
6030            import sys
6031
6032            buf = sys.stdout
6033
6034        lines = [str(type(self))]
6035
6036        if len(self.columns) == 0:
6037            lines.append(f"{type(self.index._meta).__name__}: 0 entries")
6038            lines.append(f"Empty {type(self).__name__}")
6039            if PANDAS_GT_150:
6040                # pandas dataframe started adding a newline when info is called.
6041                lines.append("")
6042            put_lines(buf, lines)
6043            return
6044
6045        # Group and execute the required computations
6046        computations = {}
6047        if verbose:
6048            memory_usage = True
6049            computations.update({"index": self.index, "count": self.count()})
6050        if memory_usage:
6051            computations.update(
6052                {"memory_usage": self.map_partitions(M.memory_usage, index=True)}
6053            )
6054        computations = dict(
6055            zip(computations.keys(), da.compute(*computations.values()))
6056        )
6057
6058        if verbose:
6059            import textwrap
6060
6061            index = computations["index"]
6062            counts = computations["count"]
6063            lines.append(index_summary(index))
6064            lines.append(f"Data columns (total {len(self.columns)} columns):")
6065
6066            from pandas.io.formats.printing import pprint_thing
6067
6068            space = max(len(pprint_thing(k)) for k in self.columns) + 1
6069            column_width = max(space, 7)
6070
6071            header = (
6072                textwrap.dedent(
6073                    """\
6074             #   {{column:<{column_width}}} Non-Null Count  Dtype
6075            ---  {{underl:<{column_width}}} --------------  -----"""
6076                )
6077                .format(column_width=column_width)
6078                .format(column="Column", underl="------")
6079            )
6080            column_template = textwrap.dedent(
6081                """\
6082            {{i:^3}}  {{name:<{column_width}}} {{count}} non-null      {{dtype}}""".format(
6083                    column_width=column_width
6084                )
6085            )
6086            column_info = [
6087                column_template.format(
6088                    i=pprint_thing(i),
6089                    name=pprint_thing(name),
6090                    count=pprint_thing(count),
6091                    dtype=pprint_thing(dtype),
6092                )
6093                for i, (name, count, dtype) in enumerate(
6094                    zip(self.columns, counts, self.dtypes)
6095                )
6096            ]
6097            lines.extend(header.split("\n"))
6098        else:
6099            column_info = [index_summary(self.columns, name="Columns")]
6100
6101        lines.extend(column_info)
6102        dtype_counts = [
6103            "%s(%d)" % k for k in sorted(self.dtypes.value_counts().items(), key=str)
6104        ]
6105        lines.append("dtypes: {}".format(", ".join(dtype_counts)))
6106
6107        if memory_usage:
6108            memory_int = computations["memory_usage"].sum()
6109            lines.append(f"memory usage: {memory_repr(memory_int)}\n")
6110
6111        put_lines(buf, lines)
6112
6113    @derived_from(pd.DataFrame)
6114    def memory_usage(self, index=True, deep=False):
6115        result = self.map_partitions(M.memory_usage, index=index, deep=deep)
6116        result = result.groupby(result.index).sum()
6117        return result

6145    def melt(
6146        self,
6147        id_vars=None,
6148        value_vars=None,
6149        var_name=None,
6150        value_name="value",
6151        col_level=None,
6152    ):
6153        """
6154        Unpivots a DataFrame from wide format to long format,
6155        optionally leaving identifier variables set.
6156
6157        This function is useful to massage a DataFrame into a format where
6158        one or more columns are identifier variables (``id_vars``), while
6159        all other columns, considered measured variables (``value_vars``),
6160        are "unpivoted" to the row axis, leaving just two non-identifier
6161        columns, 'variable' and 'value'.
6162
6163        Parameters
6164        ----------
6165        frame : DataFrame
6166        id_vars : tuple, list, or ndarray, optional
6167            Column(s) to use as identifier variables.
6168        value_vars : tuple, list, or ndarray, optional
6169            Column(s) to unpivot. If not specified, uses all columns that
6170            are not set as `id_vars`.
6171        var_name : scalar
6172            Name to use for the 'variable' column. If None it uses
6173            ``frame.columns.name`` or 'variable'.
6174        value_name : scalar, default 'value'
6175            Name to use for the 'value' column.
6176        col_level : int or string, optional
6177            If columns are a MultiIndex then use this level to melt.
6178
6179        Returns
6180        -------
6181        DataFrame
6182            Unpivoted DataFrame.
6183
6184        See Also
6185        --------
6186        pandas.DataFrame.melt
6187        """
6188        from dask.dataframe.reshape import melt
6189
6190        return melt(
6191            self,
6192            id_vars=id_vars,
6193            value_vars=value_vars,
6194            var_name=var_name,
6195            value_name=value_name,
6196            col_level=col_level,
6197        )

6244    def _select_columns_or_index(self, columns_or_index):
6245        """
6246        Parameters
6247        ----------
6248        columns_or_index
6249            Column or index name, or a list of these
6250
6251        Returns
6252        -------
6253        dd.DataFrame
6254            Dask DataFrame with columns corresponding to each column or
6255            index level in columns_or_index.  If included, the column
6256            corresponding to the index level is named _index
6257        """
6258
6259        # Ensure columns_or_index is a list
6260        columns_or_index = (
6261            columns_or_index
6262            if isinstance(columns_or_index, list)
6263            else [columns_or_index]
6264        )
6265
6266        column_names = [
6267            n for n in columns_or_index if self._is_column_label_reference(n)
6268        ]
6269
6270        selected_df = self[column_names]
6271        if self._contains_index_name(columns_or_index):
6272            # Index name was included
6273            selected_df = selected_df.assign(_index=self.index)
6274
6275        return selected_df
6276
6277    def _is_column_label_reference(self, key):
6278        """
6279        Test whether a key is a column label reference
6280
6281        To be considered a column label reference, `key` must match the name of at
6282        least one column.
6283        """
6284        return (
6285            not is_dask_collection(key)
6286            and (np.isscalar(key) or isinstance(key, tuple))
6287            and key in self.columns
6288        )

Return a subset of the DataFrame's columns based on the column dtypes.

This docstring was copied from pandas.core.frame.DataFrame.select_dtypes.

Some inconsistencies with the Dask version may exist.

Parameters

include, exclude : scalar or list-like A selection of dtypes or strings to be included/excluded. At least one of these parameters must be supplied.

Returns

DataFrame The subset of the frame including the dtypes in include and excluding the dtypes in exclude.

Raises

ValueError * If both of include and exclude are empty * If include and exclude have overlapping elements * If any kind of string dtype is passed in.

See Also

DataFrame.dtypes: Return Series with the data type of each column.

Notes

  • To select all numeric types, use np.number or 'number'
  • To select strings you must use the object dtype, but note that this will return all object dtype columns
  • See the numpy dtype hierarchy _
  • To select datetimes, use np.datetime64, 'datetime' or 'datetime64'
  • To select timedeltas, use np.timedelta64, 'timedelta' or 'timedelta64'
  • To select Pandas categorical dtypes, use 'category'
  • To select Pandas datetimetz dtypes, use 'datetimetz' (new in 0.20.0) or 'datetime64[ns, tz]'

Examples

>>> df = pd.DataFrame({'a': [1, 2] * 3,  # doctest: +SKIP
...                    'b': [True, False] * 3,
...                    'c': [1.0, 2.0] * 3})
>>> df  # doctest: +SKIP
        a      b  c
0       1   True  1.0
1       2  False  2.0
2       1   True  1.0
3       2  False  2.0
4       1   True  1.0
5       2  False  2.0

>>> df.select_dtypes(include='bool')  # doctest: +SKIP
   b
0  True
1  False
2  True
3  False
4  True
5  False

>>> df.select_dtypes(include=['float64'])  # doctest: +SKIP
   c
0  1.0
1  2.0
2  1.0
3  2.0
4  1.0
5  2.0

>>> df.select_dtypes(exclude=['int64'])  # doctest: +SKIP
       b    c
0   True  1.0
1  False  2.0
2   True  1.0
3  False  2.0
4   True  1.0
5  False  2.0

4982            The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as
4983            the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use.
4984        ascending: bool, optional
4985            Sort ascending vs. descending.
4986            Defaults to True.
4987        na_position: {'last', 'first'}, optional
4988            Puts NaNs at the beginning if 'first', puts NaN at the end if 'last'.
4989            Defaults to 'last'.
4990        sort_function: function, optional
4991            Sorting function to use when sorting underlying partitions.
4992            If None, defaults to ``M.sort_values`` (the partition library's
4993            implementation of ``sort_values``).
4994        sort_function_kwargs: dict, optional
4995            Additional keyword arguments to pass to the partition sorting function.
4996            By default, ``by``, ``ascending``, and ``na_position`` are provided.
4997
4998        Examples
4999        --------
5000        >>> df2 = df.sort_values('x')  # doctest: +SKIP
5001        """
5002        from dask.dataframe.shuffle import sort_values
5003
5004        return sort_values(
5005            self,
5006            by,
5007            ascending=ascending,
5008            npartitions=npartitions,
5009            na_position=na_position,
5010            sort_function=sort_function,
5011            sort_function_kwargs=sort_function_kwargs,
5012            **kwargs,
5013        )

Sort the dataset by a single column.

Sorting a parallel dataset requires expensive shuffles and is generally not recommended. See set_index for implementation details.

Parameters

by: str or list[str] Column(s) to sort by. npartitions: int, None, or 'auto' The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use. ascending: bool, optional Sort ascending vs. descending. Defaults to True. na_position: {'last', 'first'}, optional Puts NaNs at the beginning if 'first', puts NaN at the end if 'last'. Defaults to 'last'. sort_function: function, optional Sorting function to use when sorting underlying partitions. If None, defaults to M.sort_values (the partition library's implementation of sort_values). sort_function_kwargs: dict, optional Additional keyword arguments to pass to the partition sorting function. By default, by, ascending, and na_position are provided.

def set_index( self, other: 'str | Series', drop: bool = True, sorted: bool = False, npartitions: "int | Literal['auto'] | None" = None, divisions: 'Sequence | None' = None, inplace: bool = False, **kwargs): 
5015    def set_index(
5016        self,
5017        other: str | Series,
5018        drop: bool = True,
5019        sorted: bool = False,
5020        npartitions: int | Literal["auto"] | None = None,
5021        divisions: Sequence | None = None,
5022        inplace: bool = False,
5023        **kwargs,
5024    ):
5025        """Set the DataFrame index (row labels) using an existing column.
5026
5027        This realigns the dataset to be sorted by a new column. This can have a
5028        significant impact on performance, because joins, groupbys, lookups, etc.
5029        are all much faster on that column. However, this performance increase
5030        comes with a cost, sorting a parallel dataset requires expensive shuffles.
5031        Often we ``set_index`` once directly after data ingest and filtering and
5032        then perform many cheap computations off of the sorted dataset.
5033
5034        This function operates exactly like ``pandas.set_index`` except with
5035        different performance costs (dask dataframe ``set_index`` is much more expensive).
5036        Under normal operation this function does an initial pass over the index column
5037        to compute approximate quantiles to serve as future divisions. It then passes
5038        over the data a second time, splitting up each input partition into several
5039        pieces and sharing those pieces to all of the output partitions now in
5040        sorted order.
5041
5042        In some cases we can alleviate those costs, for example if your dataset is
5043        sorted already then we can avoid making many small pieces or if you know
5044        good values to split the new index column then we can avoid the initial
5045        pass over the data. For example if your new index is a datetime index and
5046        your data is already sorted by day then this entire operation can be done
5047        for free. You can control these options with the following parameters.
5048
5049        Parameters
5050        ----------
5051        other: string or Dask Series
5052            Column to use as index.
5053        drop: boolean, default True
5054            Delete column to be used as the new index.
5055        sorted: bool, optional
5056            If the index column is already sorted in increasing order.
5057            Defaults to False
5058        npartitions: int, None, or 'auto'
5059            The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as
5060            the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use.
5061            Only used when ``divisions`` is not given. If ``divisions`` is given,
5062            the number of output partitions will be ``len(divisions) - 1``.
5063        divisions: list, optional
5064            The "dividing lines" used to split the new index into partitions.
5065            For ``divisions=[0, 10, 50, 100]``, there would be three output partitions,
5066            where the new index contained [0, 10), [10, 50), and [50, 100), respectively.
5067            See https://docs.dask.org/en/latest/dataframe-design.html#partitions.
5068            If not given (default), good divisions are calculated by immediately computing
5069            the data and looking at the distribution of its values. For large datasets,
5070            this can be expensive.
5071            Note that if ``sorted=True``, specified divisions are assumed to match
5072            the existing partitions in the data; if this is untrue you should
5073            leave divisions empty and call ``repartition`` after ``set_index``.
5074        inplace: bool, optional
5075            Modifying the DataFrame in place is not supported by Dask.
5076            Defaults to False.
5077        shuffle: string, 'disk' or 'tasks', optional
5078            Either ``'disk'`` for single-node operation or ``'tasks'`` for
5079            distributed operation.  Will be inferred by your current scheduler.
5080        compute: bool, default False
5081            Whether or not to trigger an immediate computation. Defaults to False.
5082            Note, that even if you set ``compute=False``, an immediate computation
5083            will still be triggered if ``divisions`` is ``None``.
5084        partition_size: int, optional
5085            Desired size of each partitions in bytes.
5086            Only used when ``npartitions='auto'``
5087
5088        Examples
5089        --------
5090        >>> import dask
5091        >>> ddf = dask.datasets.timeseries(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq="1H").reset_index()
5092        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("x")
5093        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.x)
5094        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.timestamp, sorted=True)
5095
5096        A common case is when we have a datetime column that we know to be
5097        sorted and is cleanly divided by day.  We can set this index for free
5098        by specifying both that the column is pre-sorted and the particular
5099        divisions along which is is separated
5100
5101        >>> import pandas as pd
5102        >>> divisions = pd.date_range(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq='1D')
5103        >>> divisions
5104        DatetimeIndex(['2021-01-01', '2021-01-02', '2021-01-03', '2021-01-04',
5105                       '2021-01-05', '2021-01-06', '2021-01-07'],
5106                      dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='D')
5107
5108        Note that ``len(divisons)`` is equal to ``npartitions + 1``. This is because ``divisions``
5109        represents the upper and lower bounds of each partition. The first item is the
5110        lower bound of the first partition, the second item is the lower bound of the
5111        second partition and the upper bound of the first partition, and so on.
5112        The second-to-last item is the lower bound of the last partition, and the last
5113        (extra) item is the upper bound of the last partition.
5114
5115        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("timestamp", sorted=True, divisions=divisions.tolist())
5116
5117        If you'll be running `set_index` on the same (or similar) datasets repeatedly,
5118        you could save time by letting Dask calculate good divisions once, then copy-pasting
5119        them to reuse. This is especially helpful running in a Jupyter notebook:
5120
5121        >>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name")  # slow, calculates data distribution
5122        >>> ddf2.divisions  # doctest: +SKIP
5123        ["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"]
5124        >>> # ^ Now copy-paste this and edit the line above to:
5125        >>> # ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name", divisions=["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"])
5126        """
5127
5128        if inplace:
5129            raise NotImplementedError("The inplace= keyword is not supported")
5130        pre_sorted = sorted
5131        del sorted
5132
5133        # Check other can be translated to column name or column object, possibly flattening it
5134        if not isinstance(other, str):
5135            # It may refer to several columns
5136            if isinstance(other, Sequence):  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5137                # Accept ["a"], but not [["a"]]
5138                if len(other) == 1 and (  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5139                    isinstance(other[0], str) or not isinstance(other[0], Sequence)
5140                ):
5141                    other = other[0]
5142                else:
5143                    raise NotImplementedError(
5144                        "Dask dataframe does not yet support multi-indexes.\n"
5145                        f"You tried to index with this index: {other}\n"
5146                        "Indexes must be single columns only."
5147                    )
5148
5149            # Or be a frame directly
5150            elif isinstance(other, DataFrame):  # type: ignore[unreachable]
5151                raise NotImplementedError(
5152                    "Dask dataframe does not yet support multi-indexes.\n"
5153                    f"You tried to index with a frame with these columns: {list(other.columns)}\n"
5154                    "Indexes must be single columns only."
5155                )
5156
5157        # If already a series
5158        if isinstance(other, Series):
5159            # If it's already the index, there's nothing to do
5160            if other._name == self.index._name:
5161                warnings.warn(
5162                    "New index has same name as existing, this is a no-op.", UserWarning
5163                )
5164                return self
5165
5166        # If the name of a column/index
5167        else:
5168            # With the same name as the index, there's nothing to do either
5169            if other == self.index.name:
5170                warnings.warn(
5171                    "New index has same name as existing, this is a no-op.", UserWarning
5172                )
5173                return self
5174
5175            # If a missing column, KeyError
5176            if other not in self.columns:
5177                raise KeyError(
5178                    f"Data has no column '{other}': use any column of {list(self.columns)}"
5179                )
5180
5181        # Check divisions
5182        if divisions is not None:
5183            check_divisions(divisions)
5184        elif (
5185            isinstance(other, Index)
5186            and other.known_divisions
5187            and other.npartitions == self.npartitions
5188        ):
5189            # If the index has the same number of partitions and known
5190            # divisions, then we can treat it as pre-sorted with known
5191            # divisions
5192            pre_sorted = True
5193            divisions = other.divisions
5194
5195        # If index is already sorted, take advantage of that with set_sorted_index
5196        if pre_sorted:
5197            from dask.dataframe.shuffle import set_sorted_index
5198
5199            return set_sorted_index(
5200                self, other, drop=drop, divisions=divisions, **kwargs
5201            )
5202        else:
5203            from dask.dataframe.shuffle import set_index
5204
5205            return set_index(
5206                self,
5207                other,
5208                drop=drop,
5209                npartitions=npartitions,
5210                divisions=divisions,
5211                **kwargs,
5212            )

Set the DataFrame index (row labels) using an existing column.

This realigns the dataset to be sorted by a new column. This can have a significant impact on performance, because joins, groupbys, lookups, etc. are all much faster on that column. However, this performance increase comes with a cost, sorting a parallel dataset requires expensive shuffles. Often we set_index once directly after data ingest and filtering and then perform many cheap computations off of the sorted dataset.

This function operates exactly like pandas.set_index except with different performance costs (dask dataframe set_index is much more expensive). Under normal operation this function does an initial pass over the index column to compute approximate quantiles to serve as future divisions. It then passes over the data a second time, splitting up each input partition into several pieces and sharing those pieces to all of the output partitions now in sorted order.

In some cases we can alleviate those costs, for example if your dataset is sorted already then we can avoid making many small pieces or if you know good values to split the new index column then we can avoid the initial pass over the data. For example if your new index is a datetime index and your data is already sorted by day then this entire operation can be done for free. You can control these options with the following parameters.

Parameters

other: string or Dask Series Column to use as index. drop: boolean, default True Delete column to be used as the new index. sorted: bool, optional If the index column is already sorted in increasing order. Defaults to False npartitions: int, None, or 'auto' The ideal number of output partitions. If None, use the same as the input. If 'auto' then decide by memory use. Only used when divisions is not given. If divisions is given, the number of output partitions will be len(divisions) - 1. divisions: list, optional The "dividing lines" used to split the new index into partitions. For divisions=[0, 10, 50, 100], there would be three output partitions, where the new index contained [0, 10), [10, 50), and [50, 100), respectively. See https://docs.dask.org/en/latest/dataframe-design.html#partitions. If not given (default), good divisions are calculated by immediately computing the data and looking at the distribution of its values. For large datasets, this can be expensive. Note that if sorted=True, specified divisions are assumed to match the existing partitions in the data; if this is untrue you should leave divisions empty and call repartition after set_index. inplace: bool, optional Modifying the DataFrame in place is not supported by Dask. Defaults to False. shuffle: string, 'disk' or 'tasks', optional Either 'disk' for single-node operation or 'tasks' for distributed operation. Will be inferred by your current scheduler. compute: bool, default False Whether or not to trigger an immediate computation. Defaults to False. Note, that even if you set compute=False, an immediate computation will still be triggered if divisions is None. partition_size: int, optional Desired size of each partitions in bytes. Only used when npartitions='auto'

Examples

>>> import dask
>>> ddf = dask.datasets.timeseries(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq="1H").reset_index()
>>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("x")
>>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.x)
>>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index(ddf.timestamp, sorted=True)

A common case is when we have a datetime column that we know to be sorted and is cleanly divided by day. We can set this index for free by specifying both that the column is pre-sorted and the particular divisions along which is is separated

>>> import pandas as pd
>>> divisions = pd.date_range(start="2021-01-01", end="2021-01-07", freq='1D')
>>> divisions
DatetimeIndex(['2021-01-01', '2021-01-02', '2021-01-03', '2021-01-04',
               '2021-01-05', '2021-01-06', '2021-01-07'],
              dtype='datetime64[ns]', freq='D')

Note that len(divisons) is equal to npartitions + 1. This is because divisions represents the upper and lower bounds of each partition. The first item is the lower bound of the first partition, the second item is the lower bound of the second partition and the upper bound of the first partition, and so on. The second-to-last item is the lower bound of the last partition, and the last (extra) item is the upper bound of the last partition.

>>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("timestamp", sorted=True, divisions=divisions.tolist())

If you'll be running set_index on the same (or similar) datasets repeatedly, you could save time by letting Dask calculate good divisions once, then copy-pasting them to reuse. This is especially helpful running in a Jupyter notebook:

>>> ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name")  # slow, calculates data distribution
>>> ddf2.divisions  # doctest: +SKIP
["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"]
>>> # ^ Now copy-paste this and edit the line above to:
>>> # ddf2 = ddf.set_index("name", divisions=["Alice", "Laura", "Ursula", "Zelda"])
